⭐ Demonstrate VM Provisioning and Basic Management
➤ Step 1: Open Cloud Platform and Start VM Creation

• Log in to AWS EC2 or Google Compute Engine (GCP).
• Open the VM/Instance creation page from the dashboard.

➤ Step 2: Choose the Operating System

• Select a Linux OS such as:
– Ubuntu 22.04 LTS
– Amazon Linux 2 (for AWS)
– Debian/Ubuntu (for GCP)

➤ Step 3: Configure CPU and Memory

• Select a machine type according to requirements:
– AWS: t2.micro (1 vCPU, 1GB RAM – Free Tier)
– GCP: e2-micro (Free Tier)
• Modify CPU/RAM if needed for resizing demonstration.

➤ Step 4: Configure Networking and Firewall

• Enable essential ports such as:
– SSH (22) for Linux access
– HTTP (80) for web server access
• Keep default networking or select a VPC/subnet.

➤ Step 5: Launch the Virtual Machine

• Review settings and create the VM instance.
• Wait until the status shows Running (AWS) or Active (GCP).

➤ Step 6: Connect to the VM Using SSH

• Use the SSH command to access the machine:

ssh -i key.pem ubuntu@<public-ip>


• For GCP, click SSH directly from the browser console.

➤ Step 7: Install a Basic Application (Apache/Nginx)
➤ Option A: Install Apache
sudo apt update
sudo apt install apache2 -y

➤ Option B: Install Nginx
sudo apt update
sudo apt install nginx -y


• Start the service:

sudo systemctl start apache2
sudo systemctl enable apache2


(or replace apache2 with nginx)

➤ Step 8: Demonstrate VM Management Actions
➤ Start the VM

• From cloud console → Select VM → Start

➤ Stop the VM

• Select VM → Stop / Shut Down

➤ Restart the VM

• Select VM → Reboot / Restart

➤ Resize CPU and Memory

• Stop the instance
• Modify instance type (example: t2.micro → t2.small)
• Start the instance again
• New CPU/RAM values will take effect

➤ Step 9: Capture Screenshots

• Screenshots to include:
– VM creation settings (OS, CPU, RAM)
– SSH connection
– Apache/Nginx installation output
– Start, stop, restart operations
– Resizing/instance type change
